0.name: git_blob
0.description: In-memory representation of a blob object.

1.name: git_blob_lookup
1.description:
Lookup a blob object from a repository.
 The generated blob object is owned by the revision
 repo and shall not be freed by the user.

3.name: git_blob_set_rawcontent_fromfile
3.description:
Fill a blob with the contents inside
 the pointed file.

4.name: git_blob_set_rawcontent
4.description:
Fill a blob with the contents inside
 the pointed buffer

5.name: git_blob_rawcontent
5.description: Get a read-only buffer with the raw content of a blob.

6.name: git_blob_rawsize
6.description: Get the size in bytes of the contents of a blob

7.name: git_blob_writefile
7.description:
Read a file from the working folder of a repository
 and write it to the Object Database as a loose blob,
 if such doesn't exist yet.

8.name: git_commit
8.description: Parsed representation of a commit object.

9.name: git_commit_lookup
9.description:
Lookup a commit object from a repository.
 The generated commit object is owned by the revision
 repo and shall not be freed by the user.

11.name: git_commit_id
11.description: Get the id of a commit.

12.name: git_commit_message_short
12.description: Get the short (one line) message of a commit.

13.name: git_commit_message
13.description: Get the full message of a commit.

14.name: git_commit_time
14.description: Get the commit time (i.e. committer time) of a commit.

15.name: git_commit_committer
15.description: Get the committer of a commit.

16.name: git_commit_author
16.description: Get the author of a commit.

17.name: git_commit_tree
17.description: Get the tree pointed to by a commit.

18.name: git_commit_add_parent
18.description: Add a new parent commit to an existing commit

19.name: git_commit_set_message
19.description: Set the message of a commit

20.name: git_commit_set_committer
20.description: Set the committer of a commit

21.name: git_commit_set_author
21.description: Set the author of a commit

22.name: git_commit_set_tree
22.description: Set the tree which is pointed to by a commit

23.name: GIT_EXTERN
23.description: Declare a public function exported for application use.

24.name: GIT_EXTERN_TLS
24.description: Declare a public TLS symbol exported for application use.

25.name: GIT_INLINE
25.description: Declare a function as always inlined.

26.name: GIT_FORMAT_PRINTF
26.description: Declare a function's takes printf style arguments.

28.name: GIT_ERROR
28.description: Operation failed, with unspecified reason. This value also serves as the base error code; all other error codes are subtracted from it such that all errors are < 0, in typical POSIX C tradition.

29.name: GIT_ENOTOID
29.description: Input was not a properly formatted Git object id.

30.name: GIT_ENOTFOUND
30.description: Input does not exist in the scope searched.

33.name: GIT_EOBJTYPE
33.description: The specified object is of invalid type

34.name: GIT_EOBJCORRUPTED
34.description: The specified object has its data corrupted

36.name: GIT_EINVALIDTYPE
36.description: The object type is invalid or doesn't match

37.name: GIT_EMISSINGOBJDATA
37.description: The object cannot be written that because it's missing internal data

38.name: GIT_EPACKCORRUPTED
38.description: The packfile for the ODB is corrupted

39.name: GIT_EFLOCKFAIL
39.description: Failed to adquire or release a file lock

40.name: GIT_EZLIB
40.description: The Z library failed to inflate/deflate an object's data

41.name: GIT_EBUSY
41.description: The queried object is currently busy

42.name: GIT_EBAREINDEX
42.description: The index file is not backed up by an existing repository

43.name: git_repository
43.description:
Representation of an existing git repository,
 including all its object contents

44.name: git_object
44.description: Representation of a generic object in a repository

52.name: git_index
52.description: Memory representation of an index file.

53.name: git_index_time
53.description: Time used in a git index entry

54.name: git_index_entry
54.description: Memory representation of a file entry in the index.

55.name: git_index_open_bare
55.description:
Create a new Git index object as a memory representation
 of the Git index file in 'index_path', without a repository
 to back it.

56.name: git_index_open_inrepo
56.description:
Open the Index inside the git repository pointed
 by 'repo'.

57.name: git_index_clear
57.description:
Clear the contents (all the entries) of an index object.
 This clears the index object in memory; changes must be manually
 written to disk for them to take effect.

59.name: git_index_read
59.description:
Update the contents of an existing index object in memory
 by reading from the hard disk.

60.name: git_index_write
60.description:
Write an existing index object from memory back to disk
 using an atomic file lock.

61.name: git_index_find
61.description:
Find the first index of any entires which point to given
 path in the Git index.

62.name: git_index_add
62.description: Add or update an index entry from a file in disk.

63.name: git_index_remove
63.description: Remove an entry from the index

64.name: git_index_insert
64.description:
Insert an entry into the index.
 A full copy (including the 'path' string) of the given
 'source_entry' will be inserted on the index; if the index
 already contains an entry for the same path, the entry
 will be updated.

65.name: git_index_get
65.description: Get a pointer to one of the entries in the index

66.name: git_index_entrycount
66.description: Get the count of entries currently in the index

68.name: git_odb_open
68.description: Open an object database for read/write access.

70.name: git_otype
70.description: Basic type (loose or packed) of any Git object.

71.name: git_rawobj
71.description: An object read from the database.

72.name: git_odb_read
72.description: Read an object from the database.

73.name: git_odb_read_header
73.description:
Read the header of an object from the database, without
 reading its full contents.

74.name: git_odb__read_packed
74.description: Read an object from the database using only pack files.

75.name: git_odb__read_loose
75.description: Read an object from the database using only loose object files.

76.name: git_odb_write
76.description: Write an object to the database.

77.name: git_obj_close
77.description: Release all memory used by the obj structure.

78.name: git_obj_type_to_string
78.description: Convert an object type to it's string representation.

79.name: git_obj_string_to_type
79.description: Convert a string object type representation to it's git_otype.

80.name: git_obj__loose_object_type
80.description: Determine if the given git_otype is a valid loose object type.

81.name: git_obj_hash
81.description: Determine the object-ID (sha1 hash) of the given git_rawobj.

82.name: git_odb_exists
82.description: Determine if the given object can be found in the object database.

83.name: GIT_OID_RAWSZ
83.description: Size (in bytes) of a raw/binary oid

84.name: GIT_OID_HEXSZ
84.description: Size (in bytes) of a hex formatted oid

85.name: git_oid
85.description: Unique identity of any object (commit, tree, blob, tag).

86.name: git_oid_mkstr
86.description: Parse a hex formatted object id into a git_oid.

87.name: git_oid_mkraw
87.description: Copy an already raw oid into a git_oid structure.

89.name: git_repository_lookup
89.description: Lookup a reference to one of the objects in the repostory.

90.name: git_repository_database
90.description: Get the object database behind a Git repository

91.name: git_repository_index
91.description: Get the Index file of a Git repository

92.name: git_repository_newobject
92.description:
Create a new in-memory repository object with
 the given type.

93.name: git_object_write
93.description: Write back an object to disk.

94.name: git_object_id
94.description: Get the id (SHA1) of a repository object

95.name: git_object_type
95.description: Get the object type of an object

96.name: git_object_owner
96.description: Get the repository that owns this object

97.name: git_object_free
97.description: Free a reference to one of the objects in the repository.

99.name: GIT_SORT_NONE
99.description: Sort the repository contents in no particular ordering; this sorting is arbitrary, implementation-specific and subject to change at any time. This is the default sorting for new walkers.

100.name: GIT_SORT_TOPOLOGICAL
100.description: Sort the repository contents in topological order (parents before children); this sorting mode can be combined with time sorting.

101.name: GIT_SORT_TIME
101.description: Sort the repository contents by commit time; this sorting mode can be combined with topological sorting.

102.name: GIT_SORT_REVERSE
102.description: Iterate through the repository contents in reverse order; this sorting mode can be combined with any of the above.

104.name: git_revwalk_new
104.description: Allocate a new revision walker to iterate through a repo.

105.name: git_revwalk_reset
105.description: Reset the walking machinery for reuse.

106.name: git_revwalk_push
106.description:
Mark a commit to start traversal from.
 The commit object must belong to the repo which is being walked through.

107.name: git_revwalk_hide
107.description: Mark a commit (and its ancestors) uninteresting for the output.

108.name: git_revwalk_next
108.description: Get the next commit from the revision traversal.

109.name: git_revwalk_sorting
109.description:
Change the sorting mode when iterating through the
 repository's contents.
 Changing the sorting mode resets the walker.

111.name: git_revwalk_repository
111.description:
Return the repository on which this walker
 is operating.
